        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "chore: harden npm shrinkwrap release path",
        "body": "## Summary\n- Ship the root `npm-shrinkwrap.json` plus regenerated plugin shrinkwrap/package-lock metadata so dependency pins and integrity hashes are reviewed in git.\n- Add plugin npm package hardening so OpenClaw-owned plugin packages can publish explicit `bundledDependencies` when that is a good fit.\n- Add a package-level opt-out for native-heavy plugins; Codex opts out because universal bundling would ship every platform binary to every user.\n- Document shrinkwrap, plugin dependency resolution, bundled dependency tradeoffs, and the Codex opt-out in the gateway security and plugin dependency docs.\n\n## Explainer\nThis keeps two separate hardening layers:\n\n- `npm-shrinkwrap.json`: npm's publishable lockfile. It pins resolved versions and integrity hashes for npm consumers, unlike `package-lock.json`, which is normally ignored when the package is installed as a dependency.\n- `bundledDependencies`: npm's packaging mechanism for including selected dependency package folders inside the tarball. This can make plugin installs more offline/portable, but it is not free.\n\nFor normal OpenClaw-owned npm plugins, the package manifest augmentation can publish runtime dependencies as bundled dependencies. That preserves the tested dependency tree inside the plugin tarball.\n\nFor Codex, that was the wrong default. Force-collecting skipped optional native packages made the Codex tarball about 561.7 MB packed and 1.45 GB unpacked because it carried every OpenAI native binary for every OS/arch. Codex now sets `openclaw.release.bundleRuntimeDependencies: false`, so it still publishes shrinkwrap metadata, but npm resolves the host-appropriate native dependency at install time.\n\n## Verification\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs test/plugin-npm-package-manifest.test.ts`: passed, 7 tests.\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs test/package-manager-config.test.ts src/infra/update-global.test.ts`: passed, 34 tests.\n- `pnpm deps:shrinkwrap:check`: passed after rebasing onto `origin/main` and refreshing shrinkwrap metadata for `2026.5.21`.\n- `pnpm check:docs`: passed.\n- `git diff --check`: passed.\n- `AUTOREVIEW_AUTO_TESTS=0 .agents/skills/autoreview/scripts/autoreview --mode local`: fallback reviewer clean; no accepted/actionable findings.\n- Codex pack with `OPENCLAW_PLUGIN_NPM_BUNDLE_DEPENDENCIES=1`: `size=199709`, `unpacked=978628`, `bundled=0`, native bundled packages `(none)`.\n- Slack pack with `OPENCLAW_PLUGIN_NPM_BUNDLE_DEPENDENCIES=1`: `size=3981905`, `unpacked=19825530`, `bundled=114`, proving normal plugin bundling still applies.\n- Local Codex install from the opt-out tarball: `Installed plugin: codex`; plugin list showed `status=loaded`, dependency status installed/requiredInstalled/optionalInstalled all true, and npm installed `@openai/codex` plus host-native `@openai/codex-darwin-arm64`.\n- GitHub Actions on current head `aa8584bee8664572e8c14f63b4e64d079a523d41`: CI `26274952821`, Blacksmith Testbox `26274952860`, Blacksmith Build Artifacts Testbox `26274952820`, CodeQL `26274952782`, CodeQL Critical Quality `26274952818`, Workflow Sanity `26274952819`, OpenGrep PR Diff `26274952859`, Real behavior proof `26274951365`, and Dependency Change Awareness `26274951427` all passed.\n\n## Real behavior proof\nBehavior addressed: npm install hardening now supports reviewed shrinkwrap pins and optional bundled plugin runtime dependencies without forcing native-heavy plugins like Codex to ship every platform binary.\n\nReal environment tested: local macOS source checkout, Node/pnpm repo runtime, OpenClaw plugin install flow against a packed Codex npm plugin tarball, plus current-head GitHub Actions CI/Testbox proof.\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch: packed Codex with `OPENCLAW_PLUGIN_NPM_BUNDLE_DEPENDENCIES=1`, installed the resulting `openclaw-codex-2026.5.20.tgz` via `pnpm openclaw plugins install npm-pack:<tarball> --force --dangerously-force-unsafe-install`, then ran `pnpm openclaw plugins list --json` against the isolated state directory. After rebasing onto `origin/main`, regenerated shrinkwrap metadata and reran the exact failing CI shards locally before pushing `aa8584bee8664572e8c14f63b4e64d079a523d41`.\n\nEvidence after fix: Codex pack output reported `bundled=0`, `size=199709`, `unpacked=978628`; install output reported `Installed plugin: codex`; plugin dependency status was fully installed; the install root contained `@openai/codex` and `@openai/codex-darwin-arm64`, not the full cross-platform binary set. Current-head CI/Testbox workflows are green.\n\nObserved result after fix: Codex no longer produces the 561.7 MB universal native-binary tarball, while non-opted-out plugins such as Slack still publish bundled runtime dependencies.\n\nWhat was not tested: actual npm publish and current-head cross-OS Codex install after the opt-out change.\n",
